--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
THEORY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

HISTORY OF JAVA:
  -> Java was developed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems in 1991.
  -> Originally called "Oak", renamed to "Java" in 1995.
  -> Sun Microsystems released Java 1.0 publicly in 1996.
  -> Oracle Corporation acquired Sun Microsystems in 2010.
  -> Java follows the philosophy: "Write Once, Run Anywhere" (WORA).

FEATURES OF JAVA:
  1. Platform Independent : Compiled to bytecode, runs on any OS via JVM.
  2. Object-Oriented      : Everything is modeled as objects and classes.
  3. Simple               : Syntax similar to C/C++ but no pointers.
  4. Secure               : No explicit pointer, bytecode verification.
  5. Robust               : Strong memory management, exception handling.
  6. Multithreaded        : Built-in support for concurrent execution.
  7. Distributed          : Supports networking via java.net package.
  8. High Performance     : JIT (Just-In-Time) compiler improves speed.
  9. Dynamic              : Loads classes at runtime as needed.

JVM, JRE, JDK:
  +--------+------------------------------+----------------------------------+
  | Term   | Full Form                    | Purpose                          |
  +--------+------------------------------+----------------------------------+
  | JVM    | Java Virtual Machine         | Executes Java bytecode           |
  | JRE    | Java Runtime Environment     | JVM + libraries to run programs  |
  | JDK    | Java Development Kit         | JRE + compiler + dev tools       |
  +--------+------------------------------+----------------------------------+

  Flow: Java Source (.java) --> javac compiler --> Bytecode (.class) --> JVM

JAVA PROGRAM STRUCTURE:
  package com.example;          // Package declaration

  import java.util.Scanner;     // Import statement

  public class HelloWorld {     // Class declaration
      public static void main(String[] args) {   // Main method
          System.out.println("Hello, World!");   // Statement
      }
  }

